[2] England (Wales)
Date: Sat 23 Jun 2018, 4:00 PM
Source: Wales Online [edited]
https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/health/dozens-cases-measles-reported-wales-14820679


There have been more than 150 cases of measles reported in Wales since the start of the year [2018] - nearly 3 times as many as last year [2017].

Young people heading off on holiday to Europe, where there are large outbreaks of measles, are being encouraged to check they have had both MMR doses as many missed out when vaccination rates dropped in the early 2000s due to unfounded fears over the vaccine.

From the start of the year up to [17 Jun 2018], a total of 155 suspected cases of measles were reported in Wales alone to Public Health England (PHE) (which collects reports for both England and Wales).

Cases across England and Wales have now exceeded 1500 in 2018. The number of reports is 2.7 times higher than the 58 cases reported in the same 24 weeks in 2017.

Cardiff saw the highest number of reports in the first 24 weeks of the year [2018], with 41, up from 1 in the same period in 2017. It was followed by Blaenau Gwent, Neath Port Talbot and Rhondda Cynon Taf with 17 cases each, up from 2, 4 and 4 respectively, with 13 cases in Caerphilly, 7 each in Flintshire and Newport, and 6 each in Monmouthshire and Torfaen.

In the 24 weeks ending [17 Jun 2018], some 1525 suspected cases of measles were reported to Public Health England (PHE) across England and Wales.

The number of reports is much higher than over the same period in recent years. There were 713 cases reported in 2017 as well as 753 in 2016, 618 in 2015, and 1055 in 2014.

However numbers are lower than in previous outbreaks with 1985 cases reported in the first 24 weeks of 2012 and 4602 cases in the same period in 2013.

Public Health England is encouraging young people to make sure they have had both doses of the MMR vaccine before going on holiday to Europe where there are large outbreaks of measles.

[Byline: Claire Miller]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[As stated in the previous ProMED measles post, young people in England should be sure they are up to date on vaccination with MMR even if they do not plan to travel in Europe, because the infection rate in England itself is also very high. See next post as well, where the high infection rate in England is thought to be due to low immunization rate with MMR vaccine.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of England, United Kingdom can be found at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5876101,279 - Mod.LK]

