[5] Japan
Date: Sat 23 Jun 2018
Source: Outbreak News Today [edited]
http://outbreaknewstoday.com/japan-measles-outbreak-161-cases-reported-first-five-months-26060/


Japan's National International Health Regulations Focal Point (NFP) notified WHO of an ongoing outbreak of measles in Japan. From [1 Jan 2018] through [20 May 2018], 161 cases of measles were diagnosed, including 145 (90 percent) laboratory-confirmed cases.

Cases were reported from the following prefectures: Okinawa (88 cases); Aichi (25 cases); Fukuoka (17 cases); Tokyo (11 cases); Saitama (6 cases); Ibaraki and Kanagawa (3 cases from each prefecture); Yamanashi and Osaka (2 cases from each prefecture); and Chiba, Shizuoka, Hyogo, and Yamaguchi (one case from each prefecture).

Among the total cases, to date, information for 30 cases regarding their isolated measles virus genotype have been received through the national surveillance system; excluding 1 case with vaccine strain, 25 were genotype D8 and 4 were genotype B3.

Cases of imported measles continue to occur in Japan. Japan has successfully eliminated endemic measles transmission and sustained this status since March 2015 through both high vaccination coverage and rapid detection of and response to every case of measles. In 2016, routine vaccination coverage was 97 percent for the 1st dose (1 year of age) and 93 percent for the 2nd dose (year before entrance to primary school, usually 5 years of age); serological surveys have confirmed that the proportion of antibody-positive (particle agglutination titer equal or higher than 16) individuals aged 2 years or more has remained at 95 percent or above nationally.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This measles outbreak in Japan is a good example of why it is important, even in a country where endemic measles has been eliminated, to maintain a fully vaccinated population.

A Healthmap of Japan can be found at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5876101,156 - Mod.LK]

